/wiki/Bostjan_Macek: Boštjan Maček (born 17 June 1972 in Murska Sobota, SR Slovenia) is a sport shooter competing in trap. Maček represented Slovenia at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London, where he finished 7th in the qualification, with 121 rounds, thus missing the finals of best six.
/wiki/Anja_Klinar: Anja Klinar (born April 3, 1988 in Jesenice) is a butterfly and medley swimmer from Slovenia. She has competed for her native country at four Olympic Games, from 2004—2016. She represented Slovenia in the 4 × 200 m freestyle relay, 200 m butterfly and 400 individual medley at the 2004 Olympics, the 200 and 400 m individual medley at the 2008 Summer Olympics, the 4 × 200 m freestyle relay, 200 m butterfly and the 400 m individual medley at the 2012 Summer Olympics and the 200 m butterfly and the 4 × 200 m freestyle at the 2016 Olympics.
/wiki/Swimming_at_the_2009_Mediterranean: The swimming events of the 2009 Mediterranean Games were held at the Naiadi Swimming Complex in Pescara, Italy from Saturday 27 June to Wednesday 1 July 2009. Events were held in a long course (50 m) pool.
/wiki/Ur%C5%A1ka_%C5%BDolnir: Urška Žolnir (born 9 October 1981) is a Slovenian judoka. She's a member of Judo Club Sankaku Celje.
/wiki/Judo_at_the_2009_Mediterranean_Gam: The Judo Competition at the 2009 Mediterranean Games were held in Pescara, Italy from 2 to 5 July 2009.
/wiki/Alja%C5%BE_Sedej: Aljaž Sedej (born May 30, 1988) is a Slovenian judoka. He competed in the men's 81 kg event at the 2008 and 2012 Summer Olympics. At the 2008 Summer Olympics, he was defeated in the second round by Hamed Malekmohammadi.  At the 2012 Olympics he was eliminated in the second round by Travis Stevens.
/wiki/Lucija_Polavder: Lucija Polavder (born 15 December 1984 in Celje) is a Slovene judoka. Polavder competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics where she didn't advance from the first round. At the 2008 Summer Olympics she advanced to the semifinals, where she was defeated by Japanese Maki Tsukada. In the bronze medal match, Polavder defeated Korean Kim Na-Young and became the second Slovenian judoka to win a medal at the Olympics (after Urška Žolnir in 2004).
/wiki/%C5%A0pela_Ponomarenko: Špela Ponomarenko Janić (born 2 October 1981) is a Slovenian sprint canoer who has won three medals in the K-1 200 m event at the ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships with a silver in 2006 and bronze in 2007 and 2013.
/wiki/Alja%C5%BE_Pegan: Aljaž Pegan (born June 2, 1974) is a Slovenian gymnast.
/wiki/Luka_%C5%A0pik: Luka Špik (born 9 February 1979 in Kranj, SR Slovenia) is a Slovenian rower and Olympic gold medalist.
/wiki/Emil_Tahirovi%C4%8D: Emil Tahirovič (born December 30, 1979 near Ivančna Gorica, Yugoslavia) is an Olympic breaststroke swimmer from Slovenia. He swam for Slovenia at the  2004 Olympics.
/wiki/Sabina_Veit: Sabina Veit (born December 5, 1985 in Maribor) is a Slovenian sprinter. She set a personal best and an Olympic A-standard time of 22.74 seconds, by winning the 200 metres at the Slovenian Open Athletics Championships, coincidentally in her home city. She also won a bronze medal in the same distance at the 2009 Summer Universiade in Belgrade, finishing her time at 23.34 seconds.
/wiki/Athletics_at_the_2009_Mediterranea: At the 2009 Mediterranean Games, the athletics events were held in Pescara, Italy from 30 June to 3 July.
/wiki/Marko_Kump: Marko Kump (born 9 September 1988) is a Slovenian cyclist, who rides for UCI Continental team Adria Mobil.
/wiki/Ra%C5%A1a_Sraka: Russia Sraka (born 10 October 1979 in Ljubljana, Slovenia) is a Slovenian judoka. She competed in the 70 kg event at the 2012 Summer Olympics. where she lost in the quarterfinals to Hwang Ye-Sul and in the repechage to Yuri Alvear.
/wiki/Peter_Manko%C4%8D: Peter Mankoč (born 4 July 1978 in Ljubljana, Slovenia) is a Slovenian swimmer. He is one of the most successful short course European Championship swimmers in the history of the event. Mankoč is the former world record holder in the 100 meter individual medley (short course).
/wiki/Slovenia_at_the_2009_Mediterranean: Slovenia competed at the 2009 Mediterranean Games held in Pescara, Italy.
